======================================================
STEP 1 – USER LOGIN
======================================================
File: frontend/login.html

User enters username & password.
After successful login:
  → Select Project (Project View)
        → VPN Automation
             → ASA View
             → PaloAlto View

In ASA View:
  Button:
    <button onclick="runASA('update')">Update</button>

======================================================
STEP 2 – BUTTON CLICK (FRONTEND JS)
======================================================
File: frontend/app.js

Function triggered:
  runASA("update")

JS sends API request:

  fetch("/api/asa", {
      method: "POST",
      body: JSON.stringify({ task: "update" })
  })

======================================================
STEP 3 – BACKEND API ROUTE
======================================================
File: backend/main.py

Route example:
  @app.post("/api/asa")
  def asa_api(data: dict):
      return run_web(data["task"], ...)

======================================================
STEP 4 – WEB WRAPPER EXECUTION
======================================================
File: backend/projects/vpn_automation/asa/web_wrapper.py

Function:
  run_web(task, seq=None, payload=None)

Inside:

  conn = connect_asa()
  tunnels = discover_tunnels(conn)

  if task == "update":
      update_vpn(conn, payload)

======================================================
STEP 5 – UPDATE LOGIC START
======================================================
File: backend/projects/vpn_automation/asa/update.py

Entry function:
  update_vpn(conn, payload)

======================================================
STEP 6 – VALIDATION COMMANDS SENT TO ASA
======================================================

1) show run tunnel-group <peer_ip>
2) show run crypto map
3) show run access-list <acl_name>

Purpose:
  - Validate peer exists
  - Find crypto map
  - Parse ACL
  - Display CURRENT CONFIG preview

If payload["preview_only"] == True:
  → Function returns (Preview Mode)

======================================================
STEP 7 – USER SELECTS UPDATE OPTION
======================================================

Frontend modal sends second API call with:

{
  "task": "update",
  "peer_ip": "...",
  "choice": "2",
  "new_local_ip": "...",
  "new_local_mask": "..."
}

======================================================
STEP 8 – CONFIGURATION COMMAND EXECUTION
======================================================

Depending on choice:

OPTION 1 – Update Peer IP
  crypto map <map> <new_seq> set peer <new_ip>
  tunnel-group <new_ip> type ipsec-l2l

OPTION 2 – Update Local Subnet
  access-list <acl> extended permit ip <local> <mask> <remote> <mask>

OPTION 3 – Update Remote Subnet
  access-list <acl> extended permit ip <local> <mask> <remote> <mask>

OPTION 4 – Update Phase2
  crypto map <map> <seq> set ikev1 transform-set <new_ts>

OPTION 5 – Update PSK
  tunnel-group <peer_ip> ipsec-attributes
  ikev1 pre-shared-key <new_psk>

Commands executed using:
  conn.send_config_set([...])

======================================================
STEP 9 – SAVE CONFIGURATION
======================================================

conn.save_config()

Internally ASA runs:
  write memory

Configuration becomes permanent.

======================================================
STEP 10 – POST-CHANGE VERIFICATION
======================================================

Commands:
  show run crypto map
  show run access-list
  show run tunnel-group

Before vs After output printed.

======================================================
STEP 11 – DISCONNECT
======================================================

In web_wrapper.py:

  disconnect_asa(conn)

======================================================
STEP 12 – RESPONSE TO FRONTEND
======================================================

run_web() captures output using:
  redirect_stdout()

Returns full CLI output as text.

Frontend:
  asaOutput.innerText = response

Output displayed in ASA terminal window.



